AGI - Kiev has agreed on the terms of an agreement on minerals with the United States, that President Volodymyr Zelensky could sign already Friday in Washington, while Europeans will meet on Wednesday in video conferencing to point on a possible truce in the conflict in Ukraine. "I heard he was coming on Friday. This is definitely good for me. He would like to sign it with me, and I understand it: it is a big deal, a very big deal >", said Trump Tuesday at the White House. The President of the United States asked Ukraine to give it access to its mineral resources to offset the billions of dollars of aid paid by the administration of its predecessor Joe Biden. According to a high Ukrainian official who told AFP on Tuesday that Kiev was ready to sign, the Americans "removed all the clauses that were not good for us, in particular the $500 billion* that the minerals should have returned to the United States.
Washington would jointly develop mining riches with Ukraine and revenue from it would go into a newly created fund that could be "joint with Ukraine and America", according to the same source. Before the possible signing of the Friday agreement in Washington, the leaders of the 27 EU Member States will meet on Wednesday in videoconference for a debriefing of the meeting, focusing on Ukraine, between Emmanuel Macron and Donald Trump Monday in Washington. A short-term truce in the fights evoked on Monday during the visit of the French President in the United States, Russia's free way to European participation in the resolution of the conflict: Kiev's allies hope for a breakthrough after more than three years of war, while warning against an agreement that would be equivalent to a "chapter" of Ukraine.
On the ground, Russian forces continue their attacks. The Russian Ministry of Defence has declared that it has targeted "the military airport infrastructure >". Russia, which took over 20% of the Ukrainian territory, insists on the fact that it will not stop hostility until the peace negotiations lead to a result that "it suits you": calls on the Ukrainians to renounce NATO membership and to give it all or part of five occupying regions;

