AGI - A debate at the first hearing at the Court of Justice of the European Union in Luxembourg on the appeals of two asylum seekers against the Protocol Italy-Albania. At the center of the comparison, the designation of safe country and the application of the accelerated procedure for the examination of asylum requests. The applicants' defence lawyers pointed out that Article 46 of Directive 2013/32 on safe countries requires national courts to ensure an effective remedy through a comprehensive and up-to-date examination of facts and law.
&nbsp;
In particular, it has been repeatedly referred to the Court's caselaw - to the now famous judgment of 4 October 2024 in Case C-406/22 - which has clarified the importance of comprehensively assessing international protection procedures, including the designation of a third country as safe. According to Sonia Angilletta, "the only instrument to guarantee the certainty of the right is to limit the designation of a country of safe origin to cases where the conditions laid down in Annex 1 of the Directive are met throughout the territory of the State and for all categories of persons present".
&nbsp;
Annex 1 - several times referred to in more than three of the hearing chaired by the President of the Court, Koen Lenaerts - states that "a country is considered a country of safe origin if, on the basis of the legal status, the application of the law within a democratic system and the general political situation, it can be shown that there are generally and constantly persecutions as defined in Article 9 of Directive 2011/95, neither torture or other forms of conflict".
&nbsp;
According to the defence, this approach would avoid the risk of disparity in treatment between asylum seekers and that people from the same country may see themselves applying different procedures, in some ordinary cases and in other accelerated ones. The defence also denounced the detrimental effect of the accelerated procedure, which provides for extremely short periods for the submission of an appeal, as in Italy, where the deadline for appeal is only seven days. "This does not guarantee an adequate and complete examination of the question," Angilletta said.
&nbsp;
Legal Dario Belluccio, who defends another applicant, criticized the ways in which some States, including Italy, adopted the list of safe countries. "In two years, the Italian government has adopted over 20 regulatory acts on immigration and asylum, with four legislative interventions in recent months," he said. "While Italy has designated 29 states as safe, Germany has identified only 9", it continued reporting a disparity that according to the defence demonstrates an arbitrary application of the legislation.
&nbsp;
If the national court could not verify the legitimacy of the designation of a country as sure, an unjustified presumption of manifest unfounded application of asylum, which the applicant should overcome with evidence often impossible to obtain, have warned the lawyers. "An approach that undermines the effectiveness of asylum law," they added. The lawyer of the Italian State, Lorenzo D'Ascia, defended the legitimacy of the designation of safe countries, stating that the concept of security should not be interpreted in an absolute way, but rather considering the criterion of prevalence.
&nbsp;
"Security must be assessed for the majority of the population, not for the totality of individuals," he explained, recalling that the directive does not prohibit the provision of exceptions for certain categories of persons. Returning to Annex 1, for D'Ascia "the government believes that from the expression 'generally and constantly' one cannot draw the conclusion that the safety condition should be met equally for all individuals. Such an interpretation would pose a concept of safe country in an absolute sense without any margin of personal insecurity, which is desirable but undoubtedly unreal. Since it cannot give itself to the norms a meaning that is disconnected from reality, the directive obviously refers to countries that are safe for the majority of their citizens and not for all citizens, as clearly emerges from Considering 42".
&nbsp;
The representative of the Italian Government also argued that the accelerated procedure is not a derogation from international protection guarantees, but a form of efficient management of applications that do not require a complex investigation. "The right to an effective remedy is guaranteed in any case," he said, "Member States have full autonomy in defining the procedural rules for the designation of safe countries."
&nbsp;
The approach of the European Commission, Flavia Tomat, pointed out that Directive 2013/32 leaves a margin for assessment to Member States, but they must comply with the conditions laid down in Annex 1. "A country can be designated as safe only if there are no persecution generally and constantly," he said. However, the Commission acknowledged that the Directive does not exclude the possibility of providing for exceptions for certain categories of persons.
&nbsp;
"What matters is that these categories are clearly identified and that the right to an effective remedy is guaranteed," he explained. Moreover, for the Commission the concept of "generally and constantly" safe must be interpreted carefully, since some specific groups of people may not enjoy such protection. "We cannot ignore the fact that certain categories of people, such as journalists, members of religious minorities or Lgbtq+ people, may be exposed to systematic risks even in countries considered generally safe", warned the approach of the European executive. "Member States must ensure that the expected exceptions adequately cover these vulnerable groups," he said.
&nbsp;
"The Commission - it has concluded - is willing to accept that Directive 2013/32 allows Member States to draw countries of origin as safe, providing for exceptions between categories of persons". The Advocate General of the European Court, Richard de la Tour, will deliver his opinion on 10 April. The Opinions of the Advocate General do not bind the Court of Justice even if it generally addresses it. Its task is to propose to the Court, in full independence, a legal solution in the case for which it was designated. The judgment, as there is an accelerated procedure, should arrive before summer.&nbsp;
